04113nam a22006975i 9780231536455DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20142014nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2013022765  a(OCoLC)871681955  a97802315364557 a10.7312/blan166902doi  a(DE-B1597)458253  a(OCoLC)870244530  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aBS2651b.B54 2014 4aBS 7aREL0510002bisacsh1 aBlanton, Ward, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Materialism for the Masses :bSaint Paul and the Philosophy of Undying Life /cWard Blanton. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aInsurrections: Critical Studies in Religion, Politics, and Culture00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface to Politics as Materialist Spiritualities: For a Postsecular “Return” of Paulinism -- tPlatonism for the Masses: On the Sacred Cement Shoes of Paul the Apostle -- t1. Contingency; or, Covenantal Comedy: In Praise of Strange Paulinist Federations -- t2. On Being Called Dead: Splitting the Imperative of Being -- t3. Insurrectionist Risk (Paul Among the Parrhesiasts) -- t4. Singularity; or, Spiritual Exercise (Paul and the Philosophical Immanence of Foucault and Deleuze) -- t5. Seizures of Chance: Paulinist Agencies in Neocapitalist Contexts -- tConclusion: New Beginnings -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tBackmatter0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNietzsche and Freud saw Christianity as metaphysical escapism, with Nietzsche calling the religion a "Platonism for the masses" and faulting Paul the apostle for negating more immanent, material modes of thought and political solidarity. Integrating this debate with the philosophies of difference espoused by Gilles Deleuze, Michel Foucault, Jacques Derrida, Jacques Lacan, and Pier Paolo Pasolini, Ward Blanton argues that genealogical interventions into the political economies of Western cultural memory do not go far enough in relation to the imagined founder of Christianity.Blanton challenges the idea of Paulinism as a pop Platonic worldview or form of social control. He unearths in Pauline legacies otherwise repressed resources for new materialist spiritualities and new forms of radical political solidarity, liberating "religion" from inherited interpretive assumptions so philosophical thought can manifest in risky, radical freedom.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aChristianity and culture. 0aChristianity and politics. 7aRELIGION / Philosophy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066586440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/blan1669040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231536455423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231536455/original  a978-3-11-066586-4  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK